To create a for loop in Java, you can use the following structure:

for (initialization; condition; increment) {
   // code that will be repeated in each iteration of the loop
}

The initialization section is executed once at the beginning of the loop and is used to declare and/or initialize control variables for the loop.

The condition section is evaluated in each iteration of the loop and determines whether the code inside the loop should continue executing or not.

The increment section is executed at the end of each iteration of the loop and is used to update the control variables for the loop.

For example, the following code shows a for loop that prints the numbers from 1 to 10:

for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
   System.out.println(i);
}

In this case, the control variable i is initialized to 1, the condition is that i is less than or equal to 10, and in each iteration, i is incremented by 1. The result will be the printing of the numbers from 1 to 10 in the console.

